147
00:08:54,434 --> 00:08:55,634
And so why do we have eight?

148
00:08:55,634 --> 00:08:59,837
Well, this is not necessarily a magic number.

149
00:08:59,837 --> 00:09:01,879
We've just found that this is what works for us.

150
00:09:01,879 --> 00:09:05,501
So some of the reasons why include brainstorms.

151
00:09:05,501 --> 00:09:08,183
We've found that any given writer, if you give them a prompt,

152
00:09:08,183 --> 00:09:11,025
you know, write about the spring dance, they will be able to do that.

153
00:09:11,652 --> 00:09:16,236
But if you really want the story to go further and you want to make sure you're telling the best story that you can at

154
00:09:16,236 --> 00:09:21,561
this particular moment, it's good to have people to bounce ideas off of. So maybe one person will say,

155
00:09:21,561 --> 00:09:25,165
oh, you know, Autumn made that New Year's resolution where she wanted to try new things.

156
00:09:25,165 --> 00:09:29,989
Maybe we should have her try to do it. And someone else might say, well, Peyton's not going to like that because she usually

157
00:09:29,989 --> 00:09:35,254
plans all the dances. And then suddenly you have a conflict and, you know, people are working together to come up with that.

158
00:09:36,015 --> 00:09:38,296
Another reason is just for editorial and review.

159
00:09:38,296 --> 00:09:39,356
This is pretty basic.

160
00:09:39,356 --> 00:09:41,097
You don't want a lot of typos in your game.

161
00:09:41,097 --> 00:09:42,797
You don't want grammar errors.

162
00:09:42,797 --> 00:09:45,798
All of those work to throw the audience out of the game.

163
00:09:45,798 --> 00:09:49,039
So you want them immersed in it and feeling like these are real characters talking to them.

164
00:09:49,039 --> 00:09:51,820
You don't want them thinking, oh, the writer messed up and put a typo in there.

165
00:09:51,820 --> 00:09:56,801
And the last reason for us is that we're able to subdivide people up into groups.

