182
00:11:01,044 --> 00:11:04,825
And stereotypes are something that you usually hear spoken of very negatively.

183
00:11:04,825 --> 00:11:08,486
People will say something is stereotypical if they feel like they've seen it before.

184
00:11:08,486 --> 00:11:10,966
It's nothing new to them. It's kind of played out.

185
00:11:10,966 --> 00:11:13,947
But when you're trying to pack a lot of story into a small space,

186
00:11:13,947 --> 00:11:15,467
like how you're doing when you write for games,

187
00:11:15,467 --> 00:11:18,708
you don't want the story to take over or get in the way of the gameplay.

188
00:11:18,708 --> 00:11:21,069
You really want to tell the story quickly, at least in the beginning,

189
00:11:21,069 --> 00:11:22,229
and then kind of get out of the way.

190
00:11:22,670 --> 00:11:25,631
The worst thing you can see is a player spamming through dialogue

191
00:11:25,631 --> 00:11:27,652
because they feel like they just want to get to playing the game.

192
00:11:27,652 --> 00:11:30,273
And that's particularly bad for a game like High School Story,

193
00:11:30,273 --> 00:11:32,774
where the story is so much of the gameplay.

194
00:11:32,774 --> 00:11:35,635
So what we try to do is pack it in tightly in the beginning

195
00:11:35,635 --> 00:11:38,396
when you're introducing things, and then let it expand more

196
00:11:38,396 --> 00:11:39,857
when you have more time with players.

197
00:11:39,857 --> 00:11:43,118
So we use stereotypes to introduce the characters,

198
00:11:43,118 --> 00:11:45,219
but then we build on them later in later quests.

199
00:11:45,219 --> 00:11:48,480
